Use the direct three-branch implementation below:

```ts
export function clamp(value: number, minimum: number, maximum: number): number {
  if (value < minimum) {
    return minimum;
  }

  if (value > maximum) {
    return maximum;
  }

  return value;
}
```

Representative tests:

```ts
import { clamp } from "./clamp";

describe("clamp", () => {
  it("returns the minimum when value is below range", () => {
    expect(clamp(-5, 0, 10)).toBe(0);
  });

  it("returns the maximum when value is above range", () => {
    expect(clamp(15, 0, 10)).toBe(10);
  });

  it("returns the original value when already in range", () => {
    expect(clamp(7, 0, 10)).toBe(7);
  });
});
```

Review: this matches the full contract exactly. With finite inputs and `minimum <= maximum`, there are no missing edge cases beyond the specified below-range, above-range, and in-range paths.

